venv/
│
├── bin/
│   ├── activate                  # Activates the virtual environment
│   ├── activate.csh              # Activation script for C Shell
│   ├── activate.fish             # Activation script for Fish Shell
│   ├── pip                       # pip executable inside the virtual environment
│   ├── pip3                      # Python 3 package installer
│   ├── python                    # Python interpreter used in this project
│   ├── python3                   # Python 3 executable
│   ├── sigma                     # Sigma CLI executable
│   └── ...                       # Other executables installed via pip
│
├── include/
│   └── python3.13/
│       └── ...                   # C/C++ header files for compiling Python extensions
│
├── lib/
│   └── python3.13/
│       └── site-packages/
│           ├── sigma_cli/         # Sigma CLI package
│           ├── sigma/             # pySigma library
│           ├── click/             # Command-line framework
│           ├── requests/          # HTTP library
│           ├── pyyaml/            # YAML parser
│           ├── jinja2/            # Template engine
│           ├── prettytable/       # Table formatting
│           ├── urllib3/
│           ├── certifi/
│           ├── charset_normalizer/
│           ├── idna/
│           ├── packaging/
│           ├── typing_extensions/
│           ├── wcwidth/
│           └── ...                # Other Python packages
│
├── lib64 -> lib                  # Symbolic link to the lib directory (Linux)
│
└── pyvenv.cfg                    # Configuration file for the virtual environment



  What each folder means
Folder/File	Purpose
bin/	Contains all executables (Python, pip, Sigma CLI, activation scripts). This is the folder you interact with indirectly when you activate the virtual environment.
include/	Stores C/C++ header files used when compiling Python packages with native extensions. Most Python projects never touch this directory directly.
lib/	The heart of the virtual environment. It contains all installed Python libraries in site-packages.
lib64	A Linux symbolic link that points to lib. It exists mainly for compatibility on 64-bit systems.
pyvenv.cfg	Configuration file that tells Python where the virtual environment is located and which system Python it is based on.





  The Important Thing to Remember

As a cybersecurity professional, you generally do not edit anything inside venv/ manually. Python manages this directory for you.

You only interact with it by:

Activating the environment.
Installing or updating packages with pip.
Running Python or Sigma commands.

Everything else inside venv/ is infrastructure that supports your project.
